Section 1: Practical Lab 1 - Univariate Linear Regression on the California Housing Prices Dataset¶
Description for the following USE-CASE:¶

In this lab, we are about ot tackel the challenge of predicting Housing Prices in California using the Linear Regression models. We aim to understand how the population, number of houses, dependent variables act as the factors influencing the housing prices. This approach helps in identifying the key-factor of housing costs and can be useful for making informed decisions in the real estate and urban planing.

STEP-1: Loading the data¶

Source: Downloaded from Kaggle California Housing Prices

url = "https://www.kaggle.com/camnugent/california-housing-prices"

X_train_income, X_test_income, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_median_income, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

X_train_population, X_test_population, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_population, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

STEP-7: Running Linear Regression Model¶
In [8]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error

# Function to run linear regression and return parameters and errors
def run_linear_regression(X, y):
    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X, y)
    intercept = model.intercept_
    slope = model.coef_[0]
    predictions = model.predict(X)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y, predictions)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y, predictions)
    return intercept, slope, mse, mae

# Median house value vs. median income
X_income = data[['median_income']]
y = data['median_house_value']
intercept_income, slope_income, mse_income, mae_income = run_linear_regression(X_income, y)

# Median house value vs. population
X_population = data[['population']]
intercept_population, slope_population, mse_population, mae_population = run_linear_regression(X_population, y)

# Median house value vs. number of households
X_households = data[['households']]
intercept_households, slope_households, mse_households, mae_households = run_linear_regression(X_households, y)
STEP-8: Plotting Regression lines on the top of scatter plot¶
In [9]:
# Plot for median income vs. median house value
sns.scatterplot(x='median_income', y='median_house_value', data=data)
plt.plot(data['median_income'], intercept_income + slope_income * data['median_income'], color='green')
plt.title(f'Median House Value vs. Median Income\nIntercept: {intercept_income}, Slope: {slope_income}, MSE: {mse_income}, MAE: {mae_income}')
plt.show()

# Plot for population vs. median house value
sns.scatterplot(x='population', y='median_house_value', data=data)
plt.plot(data['population'], intercept_population + slope_population * data['population'], color='pink')
plt.title(f'Median House Value vs. Population\nIntercept: {intercept_population}, Slope: {slope_population}, MSE: {mse_population}, MAE: {mae_population}')
plt.show()

# Plot for number of households vs. median house value
sns.scatterplot(x='households', y='median_house_value', data=data)
plt.plot(data['households'], intercept_households + slope_households * data['households'], color='red')
plt.title(f'Median House Value vs. Number of Households\nIntercept: {intercept_households}, Slope: {slope_households}, MSE: {mse_households}, MAE: {mae_households}')
plt.show()
STEP-9: Evaluate the models¶
In [10]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
# Evaluating the performance of the linear regression using the two metrics:
# 1.mean_squared_error (MSE): measures the average squared difference between the actual and predicted values
# 2.r2-score: measures how well the independent variable explains the variability of the dependent variable

# Evaluate the model for median income
y_pred_income = model_income.predict(X_test_income)
print('Median Income Model:')
print('R-squared:', r2_score(y_test, y_pred_income))
print('Mean Squared Error:', mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_income))
print()

# Evaluate the model for population
y_pred_population = model_population.predict(X_test_population)
print('Population Model:')
print('R-squared:', r2_score(y_test, y_pred_population))
print('Mean Squared Error:', mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_population))
print()

# Evaluate the model for households
y_pred_households = model_households.predict(X_test_households)
print('Households Model:')
print('R-squared:', r2_score(y_test, y_pred_households))
print('Mean Squared Error:', mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_households))

Median Income Model:
R-squared: 0.45885918903846656
Mean Squared Error: 7091157771.76555

Population Model:
R-squared: 9.303316180364618e-05
Mean Squared Error: 13102870667.503983

Households Model:
R-squared: 0.005228201940277177
Mean Squared Error: 13035578954.783041
Conclusion:¶

In this lab, we performed univariate linear regression on the California Housing Prices Dataset to predict housing prices based on three independent variables: median income, population, and number of households. We loaded the dataset, split it into training and testing sets, trained linear regression models, evaluated their performance using R-squared and Mean Squared Error, and visualized the results with scatter plots and regression lines.
